WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.645 --> 00:00:06.270
SIMON ROGERS: Thanks
so much for coming

00:00:06.270 --> 00:00:08.119
and welcome to
[INAUDIBLE] live stream.

00:00:08.119 --> 00:00:09.650
My name is Simon Rogers.

00:00:09.650 --> 00:00:13.500
I am the news editor at Google's
News Lab, News Lab at Google.

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:15.900
And we're working some really
exciting stuff around data

00:00:15.900 --> 00:00:17.160
journalism at the moment.

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:19.560
Coming soon we have
the trends relaunch,

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:21.000
which is going to be amazing.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.220
So today is a really
great talk for us

00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:25.330
to have-- how to tell
stories with data.

00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:26.880
And we are incredibly
lucky to be

00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:29.110
joined by David
Leonhardt, who is editor

00:00:29.110 --> 00:00:31.460
of "The Upshot," which is new.

00:00:31.460 --> 00:00:32.150
How long now?

00:00:32.150 --> 00:00:32.619
It's a year, a year and a half?

00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:33.480
DAVID LEONHARDT: Just
about a year old.

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:35.063
SIMON ROGERS: Year
old and has already

00:00:35.063 --> 00:00:38.400
become one of the foremost
practitions of data journalism

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:39.390
out there in the wild.

00:00:39.390 --> 00:00:42.240
It's got great experience
about working with data.

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:44.240
He's also won a Pulitzer prize.

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:46.790
Is he the only person in here
who's one a Pulitzer prize?

00:00:46.790 --> 00:00:49.990
I'm going to say yes to that.

00:00:49.990 --> 00:00:52.430
And he's worked the
"Times" sometimes,

00:00:52.430 --> 00:00:54.180
also before that at
the "Washington Post."

00:00:54.180 --> 00:00:56.290
Has great experience
across the news industry.

00:00:56.290 --> 00:00:58.855
So without further delay,
I'll go introduce David.

00:00:58.855 --> 00:00:59.980
DAVID LEONHARDT: Thank you.

00:00:59.980 --> 00:01:01.113
Thank you all for coming.

00:01:01.113 --> 00:01:04.819
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:04.819 --> 00:01:07.330
Thanks so much for having
me, and for coming here

00:01:07.330 --> 00:01:10.626
on a beautiful day, and watching
on live stream, and all those.

00:01:10.626 --> 00:01:13.250
I've collaborated with a lot of
folks at Google over the years,

00:01:13.250 --> 00:01:15.270
and so it's really
nice to be back and be

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:16.420
talking to all of you.

00:01:16.420 --> 00:01:18.795
I want to try to give you a
little bit of the big picture

00:01:18.795 --> 00:01:22.810
sense of journalism briefly, and
then we'll talk a little bit,

00:01:22.810 --> 00:01:25.600
and then open it up to any kind
of questions that folks have,

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:27.560
whether it's about
data journalism,

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:29.184
whether it's about
the "New York Times"

00:01:29.184 --> 00:01:32.110
generally, whether it's
about anything you want.

00:01:32.110 --> 00:01:34.575
So let's start with
the big picture,

00:01:34.575 --> 00:01:36.700
and I want to start by
asking a question, which is,

00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:40.180
have you've heard the one about
journalism being in decline?

00:01:40.180 --> 00:01:41.730
It goes something like this.

00:01:41.730 --> 00:01:43.700
No one will pay for
serious journalism.

00:01:43.700 --> 00:01:47.050
Listicles, dumb down
explainers, slideshows

00:01:47.050 --> 00:01:50.350
about pets are replacing
in depth reporting.

00:01:50.350 --> 00:01:53.180
Social media has
created an echo chamber

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:55.410
in which people read only
articles that confirm

00:01:55.410 --> 00:01:57.420
their pre-existing biases.

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:01.750
The good old days of shoe
leather reporting are fading.

00:02:01.750 --> 00:02:04.180
Well, this story is wrong.

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:08.010
American journalism is better
today than it has ever been,

00:02:08.010 --> 00:02:09.120
I believe.

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:11.510
Yes, it faces some challenges,
serious challenges,

00:02:11.510 --> 00:02:12.730
real challenges.

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:16.330
The nostalgic narrative is not
completely without some truth.

00:02:16.330 --> 00:02:18.310
It has strands of truth to it.

00:02:18.310 --> 00:02:20.570
Above all, the business
model of journalism

00:02:20.570 --> 00:02:22.720
is changing rapidly
in a way that

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:26.660
does threaten some truly
valuable parts of the industry.

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:29.250
I worry in particular
about local news, which

00:02:29.250 --> 00:02:31.550
serves a really vital
role in our democracy,

00:02:31.550 --> 00:02:33.370
holding school boards,
and judges, and city

00:02:33.370 --> 00:02:37.080
councils accountable,
keeping readers informed.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:40.100
And we can talk a little bit
more about local journalism.

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:41.740
But it's important
not to confuse

00:02:41.740 --> 00:02:45.340
the challenges that are out
there with the fuller picture.

00:02:45.340 --> 00:02:48.710
The reason that journalism
matters, the reason that it's

00:02:48.710 --> 00:02:51.280
different from, say, the
horse and buggy business,

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:54.640
is that it plays a crucial
role in our democracy.

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:58.360
It helps to keep citizens
informed about the world.

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:00.400
It gives them
information on which

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:04.990
they can act as voters, as
employees, as investors,

00:03:04.990 --> 00:03:07.520
as researchers, or simply
as human beings who

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:11.650
need to eat, and exercise,
and sleep, and work, and play,

00:03:11.650 --> 00:03:13.840
and make decisions
about all of this.

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:15.440
By this standard,
by the standard

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:18.210
of whether journalism is
keeping people informed,

00:03:18.210 --> 00:03:20.690
I would argue that
journalism in 2015

00:03:20.690 --> 00:03:23.520
is stronger than it was
in 2000, is stronger

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:26.140
than it was in 1990,
or stronger than it

00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:31.710
was in those good old
days of 1950 or 1960.

00:03:31.710 --> 00:03:34.290
It's more fun, both
to practice, and I

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:36.400
think it's more fun to read.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:39.550
And I think there are four
reasons to believe this.

00:03:39.550 --> 00:03:42.500
The first is that journalism
is more accurate than it used

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:45.890
to be, which is not to say
that it's perfectly accurate,

00:03:45.890 --> 00:03:48.660
or to put it in terms that
an economist like Hal Varian

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:52.220
might use, the market
for truth is more liquid

00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:54.174
than it used to be.

00:03:54.174 --> 00:03:55.590
I want to show you
an article now.

00:03:59.374 --> 00:04:01.290
This article appeared
in the "Washington Post"

00:04:01.290 --> 00:04:02.820
a little more than 20 years ago.

00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:04.680
It's an excerpt of
a story of mine.

00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:07.350
It appeared in the
summer of 1994,

00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:09.690
and it's about behind the
scenes political efforts

00:04:09.690 --> 00:04:12.400
to build a new sports
arena in Washington.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:15.260
It would become known
as the MCI Center.

00:04:15.260 --> 00:04:17.430
Today it's the Verizon Center.

00:04:17.430 --> 00:04:20.310
It's where the Warriors
play the Wizards

00:04:20.310 --> 00:04:22.710
and the Sharks
play the Capitals.

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:25.140
I wrote this story at the
end of a summer internship

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:26.330
at the "Post."

00:04:26.330 --> 00:04:28.690
And I will confess I felt
pretty good about it.

00:04:28.690 --> 00:04:32.980
the paper stripped it across
the top of the metro section.

00:04:32.980 --> 00:04:35.600
But there is a problem
with this story,

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:38.410
and I will ask if
anyone can see it.

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:40.800
I don't expect that
anyone will, but I'm

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:43.200
happy to be
pleasantly surprised.

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:45.050
The problem is that
there is a word that

00:04:45.050 --> 00:04:48.280
is misspelled in this story,
and it's not just any word.

00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:51.300
It's Katharine, as
in Katharine Graham,

00:04:51.300 --> 00:04:53.090
the woman who ran
the "Washington

00:04:53.090 --> 00:04:55.810
Post," the newspaper in
which this article appeared.

00:04:55.810 --> 00:04:59.220
Katharine should have two A's
and one E. As you see it here,

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:03.640
it has two E's and won A. I
learned about this mistake

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:06.900
about a week later when I picked
up a copy of the Washington

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:10.000
"City Paper," which is
Washington's local weekly,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.050
and there was a small item
in it, which read, I quote,

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:15.590
"there is a special place in
the dungeon of the "Washington

00:05:15.590 --> 00:05:19.820
Post" for David Leonhardt,"
which is not exactly what you

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:22.640
want when you're a summer
intern trying to get hired.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:23.900
I did not get hired.

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:27.390
I don't know how much it had to
do with the spelling mistake.

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:30.710
Now, imagine that I
made this mistake today

00:05:30.710 --> 00:05:33.270
rather than in 1994.

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:38.000
Think about how different the
whole experience would be.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.490
The story would go online,
and in all likelihood,

00:05:40.490 --> 00:05:42.160
within a matter of
minutes, certainly

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:45.050
within a matter of hours,
some eagle eyed reader

00:05:45.050 --> 00:05:46.500
would begin mocking me.

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:49.990
It would not take an
extra week to do so.

00:05:49.990 --> 00:05:51.510
In fact, there is
a very good chance

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:53.430
that this never would
appear in the printed

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:54.810
edition of the
"Washington Post,"

00:05:54.810 --> 00:05:56.960
because the article would
go online at 9:00 AM,

00:05:56.960 --> 00:05:58.870
or 2:00 PM, or 5:00 PM.

00:05:58.870 --> 00:05:59.649
We would see it.

00:05:59.649 --> 00:06:01.190
We would feel stupid
about it, and we

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:05.150
would fix it before the
paper ever went to press.

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:07.180
Now, I know that
spelling mistakes

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:08.320
aren't really important.

00:06:08.320 --> 00:06:11.460
They may be embarrassing, but
they're not really important.

00:06:11.460 --> 00:06:15.680
But this newly liquid market
for truth is important,

00:06:15.680 --> 00:06:17.520
and it's important
for reasons that

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:20.330
are much bigger than
spelling mistakes.

00:06:20.330 --> 00:06:23.950
In the old days when
readers or sources wanted

00:06:23.950 --> 00:06:27.500
to question the conclusions
or facts in a story,

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:29.480
they didn't have
many great options.

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:31.800
They had to write a letter
to the editor, which

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:35.030
might or might not have
been published days or even

00:06:35.030 --> 00:06:38.580
weeks later, or they had to
persuade another newspaper

00:06:38.580 --> 00:06:40.690
or magazine to write
an article that

00:06:40.690 --> 00:06:43.740
came to different conclusions.

00:06:43.740 --> 00:06:46.680
Today, writers and readers
are able to hash out

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:48.790
big questions in real time.

00:06:48.790 --> 00:06:51.360
They're able to debate
them before the article has

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:53.072
settled into the consciousness.

00:06:53.072 --> 00:06:56.360
To take a tiny example,
just this weekend

00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:59.160
a journalist tweeted
an article with a chart

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:01.200
showing the Bureau
of Labor statistics

00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:03.130
series on college costs.

00:07:03.130 --> 00:07:04.880
I bet you've seen a
version of this chart.

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:06.470
It appears in the
media all the time

00:07:06.470 --> 00:07:08.220
showing how college
costs have outstripped

00:07:08.220 --> 00:07:10.090
nearly everything else.

00:07:10.090 --> 00:07:13.120
That Bureau of Labor
Statistics series is wrong.

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:15.620
It is based on a
version of college costs

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:19.180
that did not include financial
aid until relatively recently.

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:22.100
I responded saying that Bureau
of Labor statistics series

00:07:22.100 --> 00:07:22.690
is wrong.

00:07:22.690 --> 00:07:24.929
I sent a link explaining
how it's wrong.

00:07:24.929 --> 00:07:26.720
The journalist wrote
back, and said thanks,

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:29.250
and deleted the tweet.

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:34.340
This newly liquid market not
only is better for readers,

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:37.210
but it makes us
better at our jobs.

00:07:37.210 --> 00:07:40.690
As the great psychologist
Danny Kahneman says,

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:45.590
"acquisition of skills
requires a regular environment,

00:07:45.590 --> 00:07:48.430
an adequate opportunity
to practice,

00:07:48.430 --> 00:07:52.780
and rapid and unequivocal
feedback about the correctness

00:07:52.780 --> 00:07:54.820
of thoughts and actions."

00:07:54.820 --> 00:07:56.680
With the exception
of unequivocal,

00:07:56.680 --> 00:07:59.360
I would argue that
that whole definition

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:04.280
applies to social media in
particular and journalism

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:06.220
today.

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:08.480
The second reason to feel
good about journalism

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:10.170
involves the tools
and techniques

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:12.630
that we have for
telling stories.

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:15.620
If you'll permit me a
second brief personal story,

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:19.630
I joined the "New York
Times" in 1999 as a reporter.

00:08:19.630 --> 00:08:21.140
I'm happy to report
in my 16 years

00:08:21.140 --> 00:08:22.640
there I haven't I
haven't misspelled

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:26.110
Arthur or Sulzberger,
and many of the stories

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:27.970
that I write or edit
today have a lot

00:08:27.970 --> 00:08:31.320
in common with the stories
that I wrote in my first months

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:32.429
at the "Times."

00:08:32.429 --> 00:08:35.409
They're based on an academic
study or an analysis.

00:08:35.409 --> 00:08:36.960
I try to understand the data.

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:38.780
I talk to other researchers.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:41.500
I talk to policymakers about
why the study might or might not

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:42.200
matter.

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:45.200
I look for real people
who typify the trend.

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:47.360
None of that has changed.

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:50.530
Nearly everything
else has changed.

00:08:50.530 --> 00:08:54.030
When those stories went
in the paper in 1999

00:08:54.030 --> 00:08:56.010
when I joined the
paper, they likely

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:58.430
would have been accompanied
by one or two photos

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:02.600
and one or two black and
white charts or maps.

00:09:02.600 --> 00:09:06.370
Today we have so many more
tools at our disposal,

00:09:06.370 --> 00:09:10.030
and when done right, as my
colleagues are able to do-- I

00:09:10.030 --> 00:09:11.910
do not have the technical
skills to do it--

00:09:11.910 --> 00:09:15.450
those tools are
really, really good.

00:09:15.450 --> 00:09:20.180
Consider this story from 2013.

00:09:20.180 --> 00:09:22.470
This is about how the
odds of escaping poverty

00:09:22.470 --> 00:09:26.560
differ depending on
where you grow up.

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:28.450
Gone is the little
black and white map

00:09:28.450 --> 00:09:30.894
that would have accompanied
this story in 1999,

00:09:30.894 --> 00:09:32.310
and if you had
squinted back then,

00:09:32.310 --> 00:09:36.180
you might have noticed that
Utah was lighter than Georgia.

00:09:36.180 --> 00:09:40.380
Today, you can zoom in on every
metro area in the country.

00:09:40.380 --> 00:09:42.140
You can hover over
it, and you can

00:09:42.140 --> 00:09:44.780
see what the odds
of a child who is

00:09:44.780 --> 00:09:46.650
in the bottom
fifth of the income

00:09:46.650 --> 00:09:49.300
quintile growing up to
be in the top fifth.

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:51.700
You can see that those
odds are vastly worse

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:54.920
in the southeast and the
old industrial Midwest

00:09:54.920 --> 00:09:57.740
than they are in
most of California,

00:09:57.740 --> 00:10:02.360
or most of New England,
or the mountain West.

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:04.670
You can also scroll
down, and you

00:10:04.670 --> 00:10:07.040
can decide what income
group you want to focus on.

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:12.770
By any definition, this
is better journalism

00:10:12.770 --> 00:10:15.700
than we could have
done even 10 years ago.

00:10:15.700 --> 00:10:17.570
It gives readers more control.

00:10:17.570 --> 00:10:19.480
It lets them understand
the data better

00:10:19.480 --> 00:10:21.640
than they could in the past.

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:23.600
Now consider this
follow up, which

00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:25.390
we ran just a few weeks ago.

00:10:25.390 --> 00:10:28.640
It's based on the same set of
academic research, an updated

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:29.340
version of it.

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:30.670
It gets more detailed.

00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:32.530
It goes down to
the county level,

00:10:32.530 --> 00:10:34.350
and what my
colleagues did here is

00:10:34.350 --> 00:10:37.580
they set up the journalism
so that wherever you log on

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:40.420
based on the best we can
tell from your IP address,

00:10:40.420 --> 00:10:42.340
it focuses on that county.

00:10:42.340 --> 00:10:45.040
I did not have to put
Santa Clara up here.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:46.750
It came automatically.

00:10:46.750 --> 00:10:47.590
Not exactly right.

00:10:47.590 --> 00:10:49.580
Are we in Santa Clara,
or are we in San Mateo?

00:10:49.580 --> 00:10:50.280
AUDIENCE: Santa Clara.

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:51.279
DAVID LEONHARDT: We are.

00:10:51.279 --> 00:10:51.895
Exactly right.

00:10:51.895 --> 00:10:53.520
Not only that, but
if you then read it,

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:55.950
you'll see the text actually
gets into Santa Clara.

00:10:55.950 --> 00:10:59.100
There's a template in which
we give you data and text that

00:10:59.100 --> 00:11:00.760
talks about Santa Clara.

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:03.550
I think by any
definition this is better

00:11:03.550 --> 00:11:06.910
than we could have
done several years ago.

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:09.060
Here's another example.

00:11:09.060 --> 00:11:11.830
We were looking at the
relationship between family

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:15.010
income and whether a
child goes to college.

00:11:15.010 --> 00:11:17.320
The line is remarkably
straight, but we

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:19.330
thought showing people
a straight line would

00:11:19.330 --> 00:11:21.470
underestimate just how
interesting it was,

00:11:21.470 --> 00:11:25.400
so we invited them to
draw a line themselves.

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:27.590
Most people drew something
equivalent-- something

00:11:27.590 --> 00:11:36.895
like an S like that, and then
we told them what it really was.

00:11:36.895 --> 00:11:39.650
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:39.650 --> 00:11:42.030
So basically that was
not a very good line.

00:11:42.030 --> 00:11:44.710
80% of people did
better than I just did.

00:11:44.710 --> 00:11:46.390
The real line is straight.

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:48.350
We then show people
that combined

00:11:48.350 --> 00:11:50.666
answers that all readers give.

00:11:50.666 --> 00:11:51.790
This is really interesting.

00:11:51.790 --> 00:11:53.020
The situation is depressing.

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:54.690
Your family income
has a huge impact

00:11:54.690 --> 00:11:55.700
on whether you go to college.

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:58.010
It's not as depressing as our
readers think it is, though.

00:11:58.010 --> 00:11:58.280
Look.

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:00.113
Nearly all readers
underestimate the chances

00:12:00.113 --> 00:12:04.350
that poor kids go to college,
and many overestimate the odds

00:12:04.350 --> 00:12:06.469
that rich kids do.

00:12:06.469 --> 00:12:09.010
The point about all of these is
that they literally could not

00:12:09.010 --> 00:12:12.340
have existed in
1999, and whatever

00:12:12.340 --> 00:12:15.104
you think about any individual
one, whether we did it well

00:12:15.104 --> 00:12:16.770
or whether we could
have done it better,

00:12:16.770 --> 00:12:20.360
they clearly have the potential
to be better than what

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:23.410
we were doing in the past.

00:12:23.410 --> 00:12:25.440
They also have the
potential to improve

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:28.650
what I think remains the
highest form of journalism--

00:12:28.650 --> 00:12:31.870
the expose that requires
enormous work, whether it is

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:34.180
on nail salon
workers in New York,

00:12:34.180 --> 00:12:35.640
to cite a piece a
colleague of mine

00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:38.014
has recently done, whether
it's on police killings,

00:12:38.014 --> 00:12:40.180
to cite some work the
"Washington Post" has recently

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:43.310
done, it can make that
work better and easier

00:12:43.310 --> 00:12:44.640
to understand.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:45.570
One more example.

00:12:49.130 --> 00:12:52.170
This comes from
election night 2014.

00:12:52.170 --> 00:12:54.420
To be honest, election
night coverage

00:12:54.420 --> 00:12:56.360
has long been terrible.

00:12:56.360 --> 00:12:59.560
The media has exit poll results
it won't share with readers,

00:12:59.560 --> 00:13:02.030
and it generally
reports raw vote totals

00:13:02.030 --> 00:13:03.980
in a way that doesn't
explain that they

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:05.350
don't come in randomly.

00:13:05.350 --> 00:13:08.020
In some states like
Virginia, Republican areas

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:10.670
report early and
Democratic areas late.

00:13:10.670 --> 00:13:14.310
In other states like
Iowa, the reverse is true.

00:13:14.310 --> 00:13:15.850
So some colleagues
of mine realized

00:13:15.850 --> 00:13:18.580
this was possible to do better
on, and what they did was

00:13:18.580 --> 00:13:20.930
they created an
expected vote return

00:13:20.930 --> 00:13:24.350
for every county in any state
with an important election

00:13:24.350 --> 00:13:27.780
in 2014, and they then
compared the results.

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:31.700
So if a county in Virginia was
coming in 70/30 Republican,

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:34.499
but it usually came in
75/25 Republican, that

00:13:34.499 --> 00:13:36.040
doesn't mean the
Republican is ahead,

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:38.990
that means the
Republican is behind.

00:13:38.990 --> 00:13:41.520
On election night, this
was actually going live.

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:43.060
We froze it at the end.

00:13:43.060 --> 00:13:48.340
And so over time, the solid
line were the actual returns,

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:51.624
and the dotted lines were
our adjusted returns.

00:13:51.624 --> 00:13:53.290
And I can tell you
since no one had ever

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:57.260
done this before publicly, it
was quite anxiety producing,

00:13:57.260 --> 00:14:00.050
because by 8 o'clock, we
were already telling people

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:01.670
that Mark Warner
was likely to win

00:14:01.670 --> 00:14:03.220
a narrow victory in Virginia.

00:14:03.220 --> 00:14:05.550
That's the dotted blue
line that you see,

00:14:05.550 --> 00:14:07.470
whereas the raw
vote total still had

00:14:07.470 --> 00:14:11.120
Ed Gillespie, the Republican,
up by seven or eight points.

00:14:11.120 --> 00:14:14.590
And we were all
hoping against hope

00:14:14.590 --> 00:14:16.830
that the red line would
come down to the blue line,

00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:19.560
not for partisan reasons--
in fact, I'll show you Iowa.

00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:22.730
It's the flip-- because we
would have looked silly.

00:14:22.730 --> 00:14:25.210
And sure enough, these things
could go wrong sometimes.

00:14:25.210 --> 00:14:26.580
Wrong isn't even the right word.

00:14:26.580 --> 00:14:27.930
Sometimes there's
going to be uncertainty

00:14:27.930 --> 00:14:30.067
over the course of the
night, but the straightness

00:14:30.067 --> 00:14:32.150
of this blue line I think
provide some pretty good

00:14:32.150 --> 00:14:36.510
evidence that this is a better
way to think about vote returns

00:14:36.510 --> 00:14:39.080
than the raw returns.

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:43.500
You'll see the opposite
in Iowa, as I mentioned,

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:46.760
in which the Democrats starts
with a pretty substantial lead.

00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:49.390
The dotted line is
the adjusted line,

00:14:49.390 --> 00:14:52.760
and it remains quite
straight all night.

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:55.340
These interactive real
time approaches to news

00:14:55.340 --> 00:14:56.830
have all kinds of potential.

00:14:56.830 --> 00:14:59.380
For sports coverage, my
colleague, Kevin Quealy,

00:14:59.380 --> 00:15:01.930
did this delightful
NFL playoffs simulator,

00:15:01.930 --> 00:15:03.600
that if you ask
a question about,

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:08.270
I'll be more than happy to talk
about-- about personal finance,

00:15:08.270 --> 00:15:10.450
about all kinds of things.

00:15:10.450 --> 00:15:12.070
I want to make one
additional point

00:15:12.070 --> 00:15:15.620
about the new storytelling tools
that we have in journalism.

00:15:15.620 --> 00:15:18.310
One of them isn't new at all.

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:21.320
It's the new variety of
voice that journalism

00:15:21.320 --> 00:15:26.440
has always had at it's disposal,
but too often hasn't used.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:28.680
And the reason we're
getting better about voice

00:15:28.680 --> 00:15:31.510
is because of the informal
and direct culture

00:15:31.510 --> 00:15:33.917
of internet conversation.

00:15:33.917 --> 00:15:35.500
I've been a journalist
since I started

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:38.000
writing for my high school
paper almost 30 years ago.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.120
It's the only professional thing
I've ever done in many ways.

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:44.005
So I offer the following
critique in a loving way,

00:15:44.005 --> 00:15:46.590
but a lot of the traditional
style of news writing

00:15:46.590 --> 00:15:48.390
is just not very good.

00:15:48.390 --> 00:15:51.420
It consists of dense
complex sentences

00:15:51.420 --> 00:15:54.530
that begin with phrases like,
in a fundamental shift that

00:15:54.530 --> 00:15:57.390
has the potential to alter
the political landscape,

00:15:57.390 --> 00:15:59.630
and then continues
for 40 more words

00:15:59.630 --> 00:16:01.880
with various dependent clauses.

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:04.590
The web has helped to
break us of these habits,

00:16:04.590 --> 00:16:06.210
or at least it's starting to.

00:16:06.210 --> 00:16:09.320
We now more frequently write
in a conversational voice,

00:16:09.320 --> 00:16:11.480
an understandable
style that allows

00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:16.780
smart non-experts to engage
with our material more easily.

00:16:16.780 --> 00:16:18.580
This change isn't revolutionary.

00:16:18.580 --> 00:16:19.790
None of us invented it.

00:16:19.790 --> 00:16:23.010
Kate Boo, Michael Lewis,
Robert Caro, Taylor Branch,

00:16:23.010 --> 00:16:25.780
other great writers have been
writing this way for decades.

00:16:25.780 --> 00:16:28.300
"Slate," which is a forerunner
of today's journalism

00:16:28.300 --> 00:16:31.160
in so many ways, has
been doing it for years,

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:33.090
but I'm happy that
more of us are now

00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:37.010
attempting this approach rather
than the stultified approach.

00:16:37.010 --> 00:16:38.250
And let's be clear.

00:16:38.250 --> 00:16:42.070
There is nothing inherently
sophisticated or smart

00:16:42.070 --> 00:16:46.656
about a 40 word sentence with
a lot of grandiose words in it.

00:16:46.656 --> 00:16:48.280
The third reason
journalism is stronger

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:50.488
is actually a reason I've
already covered stealthily.

00:16:50.488 --> 00:16:51.630
It's about the data.

00:16:51.630 --> 00:16:54.710
We have better data
than we used to.

00:16:54.710 --> 00:16:57.420
Data sometimes gets fetishized,
and probably more often it

00:16:57.420 --> 00:16:59.840
gets maligned as
somehow inhuman,

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:01.290
which is obviously silly.

00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:04.030
Data is just the plural
of fact collected

00:17:04.030 --> 00:17:06.140
in a way that allows for
meaningful comparisons

00:17:06.140 --> 00:17:08.390
when it's done
right, but we really

00:17:08.390 --> 00:17:11.200
do have better data and a
better picture of reality

00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:12.290
than we used to.

00:17:12.290 --> 00:17:15.150
Those studies I showed you about
the odds of escaping poverty

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:16.950
would not have been
possible before.

00:17:16.950 --> 00:17:19.450
They're based on administrative
data that follow people over

00:17:19.450 --> 00:17:22.430
many years and track their
earnings in a way that surveys

00:17:22.430 --> 00:17:23.650
simply cannot do.

00:17:23.650 --> 00:17:26.490
You cannot survey enough people,
and continue to follow them,

00:17:26.490 --> 00:17:29.100
and expect them to answer
accurately about their earnings

00:17:29.100 --> 00:17:31.710
in the way that
administrative data does.

00:17:31.710 --> 00:17:33.371
We don't just have
administrative data.

00:17:33.371 --> 00:17:35.870
We have all kinds of data from
the web that gives us insight

00:17:35.870 --> 00:17:37.670
into what people are
doing and what people

00:17:37.670 --> 00:17:41.622
are thinking as they are doing
it and as they are thinking it.

00:17:41.622 --> 00:17:44.080
We've collaborated with Google
on a bunch of such projects,

00:17:44.080 --> 00:17:45.910
including a fun piece
from Thanksgiving

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:48.630
about the regional
variations in recipes

00:17:48.630 --> 00:17:50.920
that people search for
on Thanksgiving week.

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:53.130
Thanks to that, I
and readers know

00:17:53.130 --> 00:17:56.980
what frog eye salad is, which
I do not recommend you eat.

00:17:56.980 --> 00:17:58.980
And we know what
chocolate chess bars are,

00:17:58.980 --> 00:18:00.790
which I do recommend you eat.

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:04.080
We also know that Jewish apple
cake is popular in Pennsylvania

00:18:04.080 --> 00:18:06.830
and not at all Jewish.

00:18:06.830 --> 00:18:10.030
The final reason that I
think journalism is stronger

00:18:10.030 --> 00:18:11.950
is that the market says so.

00:18:11.950 --> 00:18:14.010
The audience for
ambitious journalism

00:18:14.010 --> 00:18:16.889
is larger than it was
only a short time ago.

00:18:16.889 --> 00:18:18.930
The number of people who
read a typical big story

00:18:18.930 --> 00:18:22.670
at the "Times" has increased
probably 50% or 100%

00:18:22.670 --> 00:18:25.200
since I joined the
paper, and many of them

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:28.370
are paying for it, either
through a paper subscription

00:18:28.370 --> 00:18:30.350
or an online subscription.

00:18:30.350 --> 00:18:34.690
Beyond the "Times," a potpourri
of really good new publications

00:18:34.690 --> 00:18:37.280
have arisen, replacing some
of the famous brands that

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:38.040
have faded.

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:41.080
"Quartz," "Vox," "Buzzfeed,"
"FiveThirtyEight"-- I already

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:42.150
mentioned "Slate."

00:18:42.150 --> 00:18:44.790
And while the "Atlantic" and
the "New Yorker" are old names,

00:18:44.790 --> 00:18:48.290
they're doing new things,
and they're doing them well.

00:18:48.290 --> 00:18:50.210
Just as important,
readers are making clear

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:55.051
that they want more of the
new forms of journalism.

00:18:55.051 --> 00:18:57.550
If you look at the list of the
most read stories on the "New

00:18:57.550 --> 00:19:00.120
York Times" over
any extended period,

00:19:00.120 --> 00:19:02.480
you'll notice a few
fascinating patterns.

00:19:02.480 --> 00:19:05.190
First, of course there
are articles about diet,

00:19:05.190 --> 00:19:09.270
and exercise, and
sex, and real estate,

00:19:09.270 --> 00:19:12.160
but that's not what most of
the best read particles are.

00:19:12.160 --> 00:19:14.210
Most of the best read
articles are about subjects

00:19:14.210 --> 00:19:17.530
that no one would ever
describe as click bait,

00:19:17.530 --> 00:19:20.950
but I find this pattern
may be even more important.

00:19:20.950 --> 00:19:24.090
A disproportionate share of the
most read articles at the "New

00:19:24.090 --> 00:19:27.720
York Times" are not
articles, at least not

00:19:27.720 --> 00:19:29.290
in the traditional sense.

00:19:29.290 --> 00:19:32.140
They're interactives, like the
ones I've been showing you.

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:32.750
They're maps.

00:19:32.750 --> 00:19:33.440
They're photos.

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:34.850
They're essays.

00:19:34.850 --> 00:19:35.810
They're videos.

00:19:35.810 --> 00:19:36.920
They're Q&amp;A's.

00:19:36.920 --> 00:19:39.170
They're often highly
substantive pieces

00:19:39.170 --> 00:19:42.160
of work about serious topics.

00:19:42.160 --> 00:19:44.500
They're just not in
the form around which

00:19:44.500 --> 00:19:49.280
we've traditionally organized
journalism-- blocks of text.

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:52.160
You see it not just with what
we're doing at "The Upshot."

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:53.920
You see it through
an Ebola explainer.

00:19:53.920 --> 00:19:55.755
You see through ISIS videos.

00:19:55.755 --> 00:19:58.130
You see it through things
we've done on "Game of Thrones"

00:19:58.130 --> 00:20:00.770
and on how people age.

00:20:00.770 --> 00:20:02.890
I'm not suggesting
that journalism abandon

00:20:02.890 --> 00:20:04.455
the traditional
article, and if this

00:20:04.455 --> 00:20:05.830
were a journalistic
audience, I'd

00:20:05.830 --> 00:20:08.850
spend five minutes assuring
you I'm not suggesting that,

00:20:08.850 --> 00:20:11.960
but I do think that readers
are telling us something here,

00:20:11.960 --> 00:20:14.240
and I think we could do
a better job of listening

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:15.590
than we are doing.

00:20:15.590 --> 00:20:18.370
The smartest, clearest
way to tell a story

00:20:18.370 --> 00:20:22.830
isn't always the way we would
have told it a generation ago.

00:20:22.830 --> 00:20:25.010
It's especially
important for journalism

00:20:25.010 --> 00:20:28.960
to listen to this message and
to others, to be self critical,

00:20:28.960 --> 00:20:31.840
and to be open to change,
because we really are

00:20:31.840 --> 00:20:33.840
dealing with some challenges.

00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:37.240
As I mentioned at the beginning,
our old business model

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:41.250
has disappeared, and we don't
know exactly what the new one

00:20:41.250 --> 00:20:42.170
looks like.

00:20:42.170 --> 00:20:45.860
On the one hand, I believe there
is a large market of people

00:20:45.860 --> 00:20:48.750
who are willing to pay
for good information

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:53.160
about the world directly through
subscriptions or indirectly

00:20:53.160 --> 00:20:55.830
through advertising,
but the fact

00:20:55.830 --> 00:20:58.170
is that the best
journalism has depended

00:20:58.170 --> 00:21:02.600
on cross subsidies for
decades, if not centuries.

00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:05.010
In the second half
of the 20th century,

00:21:05.010 --> 00:21:07.740
those cross subsidies
came thanks to local quasi

00:21:07.740 --> 00:21:11.160
monopolies-- newspapers--
that could use the revenue

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:14.770
from retail, and help
wanted, and other advertising

00:21:14.770 --> 00:21:18.860
to provide a public good--
information about society

00:21:18.860 --> 00:21:24.110
that educated readers and that
was often expensive to compile.

00:21:24.110 --> 00:21:25.940
It's not like that
information was

00:21:25.940 --> 00:21:27.860
an entirely self
sustaining business

00:21:27.860 --> 00:21:30.250
before the internet came along.

00:21:30.250 --> 00:21:32.530
It was partially
self sustaining,

00:21:32.530 --> 00:21:35.070
and it can continue to
be at least partially

00:21:35.070 --> 00:21:36.710
self sustaining.

00:21:36.710 --> 00:21:39.390
The main business
task facing journalism

00:21:39.390 --> 00:21:43.000
is to think about what new
services and new revenue

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.400
might replace those
old cross subsidies.

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:50.960
The main journalistic task is
to think openly and creatively

00:21:50.960 --> 00:21:55.040
about the new tools that we
have to use them to give readers

00:21:55.040 --> 00:21:57.800
the clearest, most
accurate, most

00:21:57.800 --> 00:22:00.670
meaningful picture of reality.

00:22:00.670 --> 00:22:03.140
That's what journalism is.

00:22:03.140 --> 00:22:05.650
It's all that it
has ever been in,

00:22:05.650 --> 00:22:10.220
and it's what it will continue
to be, regardless of the form

00:22:10.220 --> 00:22:12.680
in which it is delivered.

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:14.920
Thank you for having me and
thank you for listening.

00:22:14.920 --> 00:22:16.678
I look forward to
your questions.

00:22:16.678 --> 00:22:20.219
[APPLAUSE]

